<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-10-29T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-10-29T09:00:00-05:00" n="507" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d507">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">871.014 Bessarabia/5: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-10-29T15:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">October 29,
                                        1920—3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 6:55
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1866. Mission. Bessarabian treaty was signed October 28th by Cambon,
                            Derby, Jonesco,<note n="8" xml:id="d507fn8">Take Jonesco, Rumanian
                                Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> and Ghika.<note n="9" xml:id="d507fn9">Prince Dimitrie Ghika, Rumanian Minister to
                                France.</note> Ishii being at Brussels, treaty was left open for his
                                signature<note n="10" xml:id="d507fn10">Viscount Ishii signed on
                                Oct. 30.</note> as well [as] for those of British Dominions.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>